title: Enable Midstream Breaches Its 52-Week Low on Wednesday, July 8
text:
Upstream MLPs Fall as Crude Supplies Continue to Rise Worst performers 
Enable Midstream (ENBL) was the worst performer among midstream MLPs (master limited partnerships) at the end of trading on Wednesday, July 8. It fell 4.92% in a single trading session yesterday. Enable Midstream Partners 
Enable Midstream breached its 52-week low yesterday. Now, its new 52-week low is $14.44. The stock has returned -24.19% YTD (year-to-date). Enable Midstream provides natural gas gathering, processing, transportation, and storage services. Valero Energy Partners 
Next on our list of the worst midstream MLP performers on July 8 is Valero Energy Partners (VLP). It fell 3.88% yesterday. However, it has returned 13.34% YTD. Valero Energy Partners’ solid YTD market performance can be attributed to its above normal distribution growth. Its 1Q15 distribution grew by 31% YoY (year-over-year) during 1Q14. Valero Energy Partners was formed by Valero Energy (VLO) to own, operate, develop, and acquire crude oil and refined petroleum products pipelines, terminals, and other transportation and logistics assets. Other worst performers 
Tallgrass Energy Partners (TEP), Genesis Energy (GEL), and Crestwood Midstream Partners (CMLP) were among the top five worst midstream MLP performers on Wednesday, July 8. They fell 3.33%, 3.27%, and 3.07% in the last trading session, respectively. They’ve returned 1.99%, 3.82%, and -27.21% YTD, respectively. 
Crestwood Midstream Partners has lost over one-fourth of its market value—mainly due to low NGL (natural gas liquid) and crude oil prices affecting its’s Crude Oil and NGLs services segment. Read Crestwood Midstream and Crestwood Equity Will Merge: Is It a Turning Point? for a detailed analysis of its recent performance. 
The Alerian MLP ETF (AMLP) is comprised of 25 midstream MLPs. It has returned -11.53% YTD. Together, Genesis Energy and Crestwood Midstream Partners account for ~4.36% of AMLP. For context, the upstream energy company heavy SPDR S&P Oil & Gas Exploration & Production ETF (XOP) has returned -9.65% YTD.
